        -:  190:
        -:  191:/** \var fix<N>()
        -:  192:  * \ingroup Core_Module
        -:  193:  *
        -:  194:  * This \em identifier permits to construct an object embedding a compile-time integer \c N.
        -:  195:  *
        -:  196:  * \tparam N the compile-time integer value
        -:  197:  *
        -:  198:  * It is typically used in conjunction with the Eigen::seq and Eigen::seqN functions to pass compile-time values to them:
        -:  199:  * \code
        -:  200:  * seqN(10,fix<4>,fix<-3>)   // <=> [10 7 4 1]
        -:  201:  * \endcode
        -:  202:  *
        -:  203:  * See also the function fix(int) to pass both a compile-time and runtime value.
        -:  204:  *
        -:  205:  * In c++14, it is implemented as:
        -:  206:  * \code
        -:  207:  * template<int N> static const internal::FixedInt<N> fix{};
        -:  208:  * \endcode
        -:  209:  * where internal::FixedInt<N> is an internal template class similar to
        -:  210:  * <a href="http://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/types/integral_constant">\c std::integral_constant </a><tt> <int,N> </tt>
        -:  211:  * Here, \c fix<N> is thus an object of type \c internal::FixedInt<N>.
        -:  212:  *
        -:  213:  * \sa fix<N>(int), seq, seqN
        -:  214:  */
        -:  215:template<int N>
        -:  216:static const auto fix();
        -:  217:
        -:  218:/** \fn fix<N>(int)
        -:  219:  * \ingroup Core_Module
        -:  220:  *
        -:  221:  * This function returns an object embedding both a compile-time integer \c N, and a fallback runtime value \a val.
        -:  222:  *
        -:  223:  * \tparam N the compile-time integer value
        -:  224:  * \param  val the fallback runtime integer value
        -:  225:  *
        -:  226:  * This function is a more general version of the \ref fix identifier/function that can be used in template code
        -:  227:  * where the compile-time value could turn out to actually mean "undefined at compile-time". For positive integers
        -:  228:  * such as a size or a dimension, this case is identified by Eigen::Dynamic, whereas runtime signed integers
        -:  229:  * (e.g., an increment/stride) are identified as Eigen::DynamicIndex. In such a case, the runtime value \a val
        -:  230:  * will be used as a fallback.
        -:  231:  *
        -:  232:  * A typical use case would be:
        -:  233:  * \code
        -:  234:  * template<typename Derived> void foo(const MatrixBase<Derived> &mat) {
        -:  235:  *   const int N = Derived::RowsAtCompileTime==Dynamic ? Dynamic : Derived::RowsAtCompileTime/2;
        -:  236:  *   const int n = mat.rows()/2;
        -:  237:  *   ... mat( seqN(0,fix<N>(n) ) ...;
        -:  238:  * }
        -:  239:  * \endcode
        -:  240:  * In this example, the function Eigen::seqN knows that the second argument is expected to be a size.
        -:  241:  * If the passed compile-time value N equals Eigen::Dynamic, then the proxy object returned by fix will be dissmissed, and converted to an Eigen::Index of value \c n.
        -:  242:  * Otherwise, the runtime-value \c n will be dissmissed, and the returned ArithmeticSequence will be of the exact same type as <tt> seqN(0,fix<N>) </tt>.
        -:  243:  *
        -:  244:  * \sa fix, seqN, class ArithmeticSequence
        -:  245:  */
        -:  246:template<int N>
        -:  247:static const auto fix(int val);
        -:  248:
        -:  249:#endif // EIGEN_PARSED_BY_DOXYGEN
        -:  250:
        -:  251:} // end namespace Eigen
